Two different prime numbers between $4$ and $18$ are chosen. When their sum is subtracted from their product, which of the following numbers could be obtained? $$
\text A. \ \ 21 \qquad \text B. \ \ 60 \qquad \text C. \ \ 119 \qquad \text D. \ \ 180 \qquad \text E. \ \ 231
$$
inference:
Solution:
The only two primes between $4$ and $18$ are $5$ and $13$. Their sum is $5+13=18$ and their product is $5\cdot13=65$. Subtracting the sum from the product gives $65-18=\boxed{47}$.
Final Answer: \boxed{$47$}. I hope it is correct.
ground_truth: There are five prime numbers between $4$ and $18:$ namely $5,$ $7,$ $11,$ $13,$ and $17.$ Hence the product of any two of these is odd and the sum is even. Because $$xy-(x+y)=(x-1)(y-1)-1$$increases as either $x$ or $y$ increases (since both $x$ and $y$ are bigger than $1$), the answer must be an odd number that is no smaller than $$23=5\cdot 7-(5+7)$$and no larger than $$191=13\cdot 17-(13+17).$$The only possibility among the options is $\boxed{119},$ and indeed $119=11\cdot 13-(11+13).$
